response:
```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    "Pressure Sensor Array" -> "Instrumentation Amplifiers" -> "Multiplexer" -> "Anti-Aliasing Filter" -> "ADC" -> "Data Interface";
    "Temperature Sensor Array" -> "Signal Conditioner (Nonlinearity Correction)" -> "Voltage Amplifiers" -> "Multiplexer" -> "Anti-Aliasing Filter";
}
```

```Explanations
Pressure Sensor Array: This block consists of eight strain-gauge pressure sensors, each producing a maximum output of 1 mV. Their purpose is to accurately measure pressure at various points of the machine.

Instrumentation Amplifiers: These amplifiers are used to boost the low-voltage signals from the pressure sensors while maintaining a high input impedance. They also provide necessary gain while rejecting common-mode noise.

Signal Conditioner (Nonlinearity Correction): Since the temperature sensors have a nonlinear output, this block is responsible for converting the nonlinear voltage levels to a linear scale, facilitating accurate temperature measurement.

Temperature Sensor Array: This block represents eight infrared radiation detectors used for surface temperature measurement. The sensors produce a maximum output of 100 mV and have a nonlinear response to temperature.

Voltage Amplifiers: These amplify the conditioned temperature signals to suitable levels for the multiplexer and ADC, ensuring that the full dynamic range of the ADC is utilized.

Multiplexer: Given that the ADC samples one channel at a time, the multiplexer sequentially selects each of the pressure and temperature sensor outputs, directing them to the ADC.

Anti-Aliasing Filter: A low-pass filter that removes frequencies higher than 400 Hz to prevent aliasing. This filter is placed before the ADC to ensure that the sampled data is free from unwanted high-frequency components.

ADC: The analog-to-digital converter transforms the analog signals from the pressure and temperature sensors into digital data for analysis. It should sample at a rate sufficient to capture signals up to 400 Hz (at least 800 samples per second per Nyquist criterion).

Data Interface: This block represents the interface through which the digital data is sent to the computer for analysis. It ensures reliable data transmission and may include serial, USB, Ethernet, or other communication protocols.
```

